<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98648902093985></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98648902093985><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=98648902093985>RE: Why not DE?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=98648902093985#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Apr 5th 12:43 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Although my mage is an Erudite, and I do believe they make excellent mages, I have to say a few words about whether they make the "best" mage.<br><br>Stats aren't nearly as important in the game as you might think, especially in the early years. By the time your INT really matters in the game, you've started finding good items which add to this statistic, so your starting INT alone isn't such a big factor in determining your race.<br><br>I leveled to 8 in Toxxulia, and it's not as bad an area as it is made out to be by those who would rather have fifty bats within arms reach of the town gate. However, it can be a little frustrating up until you get a good light source at level 4. If you do start as an Erudite, get the True North spell as early as you can and use it to find your way back to town if you get lost. Also, there are only three summoned pets in the zone, so Sense Summoned at level 4 can help you find some good landmarks. Other than that, the important landmarks and camping areas in the zone (druid ring, wizard spires, small kobald camp, heretic pet hut) are fairly easy to find if you just stick to the zone walls and the river.<br><br>The biggest problem with starting as an Erudite is your faction. Erudites start out with the most restrictive starting faction of all the "good" races. You can train in Freeport, which is nice, but expect to kill a lot of gnolls and bandits before Qeynos or Highpass citizens will even talk to you.<br><br>I completely agree about the funk, though.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
