<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9861213459970></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9861213459970><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9861213459970>RE: How to outdamage your pet?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9861213459970#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Apr 1st 6:35 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Sometimes your pet is going to outdamage you; you do still get experience from the kill, just not quite as much as you normally would. In fact, if your pet can outdamage you and not take too much damage, you can earn experience quite a bit faster by letting it mostly solo mobs while you conserve mana.<br><br>Going after red and yellow mobs is what is hurting you the most here. Those mobs are resisting a bit more of your damage, and they have more hitpoints due to their level, so it's taking you more nukes to take them down.<br><br>Your best bet is to find a place with some blue/even/low yellow mobs you can kill, preferably mobs with fewer hitpoints for there level than average. Lavastorm Mountains is a great example; mobs like lava basilisks and fire elementals don't have a lot of hitpoints for their level because they have magical attacks. In the case of the basilisks, you can easily avoid the stun attack since your pet will be up front taking the damage (and it seems to recover very fast from this type of spell), and in the case of elementals, you can dispell the damage shield with Cancel Magic. The result is some pretty fast experience and excellent loot for your level.<br><br>Also, you don't have to use your biggest nukes all the time. Often, you can do more damage for less mana if you stick to one or two spells from earlier levels, and keep one current spell memorized for when you need to really do some damage quickly.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98633049356970></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98633049356970><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=98633049356970>RE: How to outdamage your pet?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=98633049356970#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=887><span id=Sage>Zuranthium</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>385 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Apr 3rd 4:41 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I am not really seeing how you can not outdamage your pet at your level. Unless your pet is wielding a weapon that makes it hit for 20 or more damage, then you should have no problems at your level. For example, if you are fighting wisps, then 4 or 5 nukes will be enough to outdamage your pet. If you have 156 int, then 4 or 5 nukes should only be 2 bubbles of mana. At your level 2 bubbles of mana only means 2 minutes of downtime. <br>     I think your problem might be that you are trying to outdamage your pet TOO much. Do a practice fight on whatever you are fighting to see about how much HP it has. The next time you go into a fight, try to do 55-60% of the damage to your creature with your nukes. You don't need to do more than that.<br><br>Former Everquest Addict.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
