<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9861222279969></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9861222279969><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9861222279969>RE: Pets</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=9861222279969#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sun, Apr 1st 6:50 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>To answer the last part first: yes, especially at lower levels (when you are prone to soloing), the earth and water pets are generally the best because they are more durable.<br><br>Quick run down of the pets:<br><br>Water: Very resistant (possibly immune) to poison, highest hitpoint regeneration. Good agility, good hit points, good physical damage, good cold based damage attack. An excellent choice for an all-purpose pet.<br><br>Earth: Highest hitpoints, poor AC (so it gets hit more often). Generally highest physical damage. No damage spell (until very high levels, and then it's not much damage), but casts a weak root spell often. Good choice for soloing, although root will break much more often than a typcial caster's root spell will. Since its spell does not do damage, earth is a good choice for situations where you would otherwise be outdamaged by your pet.<br><br>Air: Decent hitpoints, decent physical damage, excellent AC (gets hit less often, and for less damage, than other pets). Casts a stun spell which does not do damge (until high levels) but does disrupt casting. The air pet does not come into its own until after at least level 20; at that point, it is an excellent pet for grouping and for facing caster mobs. Also casts invisibility on itself when not otherwise occupied.<br><br>Fire: Poor hitpoints, decent AC, poor physical damage. Casts a damage shield which, at all levels, returns more damage than whatever spell you currently have. Casts a good fire damage spell. At high levels, casts a variety of fire spells. Poor choice in general up to about level 20, but after that a great group choice, or for facing mobs which hit very often but for only moderate damage per round (typically, your monk-type mobs). For obvious reasons, not the best choice against mobs with high fire resistance.<br><br>At low levels, when you don't have much money to spare, pick either earth or water as your normal companion. The fire and air pets aren't really spectacular at these levels anyway. At level 20, purchase all your pets, and thereafter purchase or research all pets at each level. Each pet really does have some areas in which it shines, and you'll appreciate having the best pet for the job.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
